04094nam a22006735i 9780814705292DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20032003nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147052927 a10.18574/nyu/9780814705292.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548378  a(OCoLC)58836555  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF9325 .A93 2003 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a342.73/0851 aAbramson, Paul R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSexual Rights in America :bThe Ninth Amendment and the Pursuit of Happiness /cSteven D. Pinkerton, Mark Huppin, Paul R. Abramson. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2003] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Sex and the Constitution -- t2. History and Interpretation of the Ninth Amendment -- t3. The Poverty of Privacy -- t4. A Solid Foundation for Sexual Rights -- t5. What Can We Learn from Dial-a-Porn? -- t6. Does Prostitution Deserve Constitutional Protection? -- t7. Child Pornography -- t8. The Past and Future of the Ninth Amendment -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Constitution of the United States guarantees all Americans certain rights, such as the freedoms of speech and religious expression. But what guarantees our sexual freedoms? Sexual Rights in America presents a bold and intriguing look at the constitutional basis of sexual rights in America. Resurrecting the "forgotten" Ninth Amendment, which guarantees those fundamental rights not protected elsewhere in the Constitution, Abramson and colleagues argue that the freedom to choose how, when, and with whom we express ourselves sexually is integral to our happiness. Their careful review of the historical record reveals the importance of the "pursuit of happiness" in the socio-moral philosophy underpinning the Constitution. Sexual freedoms, they assert, are cut from the same cloth as the other freedoms protected by the Bill of Rights, and therefore, should be covered by the Ninth Amendment. Using concrete examples such as prostitution and phone sex, Sexual Rights in America illustrates the scope and limitations of Ninth Amendment sexual rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSex and lawzUnited States. 0aSexual rightszUnited States. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh1 aHuppin, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPinkerton, Steven D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081470692340uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814705292.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814705292423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814705292/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles